  "case_id": "D2N072",
  "method": "cap_event",
  "template": "sectioned",
  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nRight index finger pain following a skiing injury.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports right index finger pain following a skiing injury over the weekend. He sustained a strap caught on his finger while jumping moguls, resulting in a bend in the finger. He initially tried ice and ibuprofen, but the pain persists. He describes the pain as worsening with movement and reports tenderness at the distal phalanx and the joint itself. He has no prior surgeries and reports constipation treated with miralax.\n\nFindings\nPhysical examination reveals tenderness over the distal phalanx and the joint of the right index finger. Range of motion is limited, with pain on flexion. X-rays demonstrate no fractures and normal alignment of the finger joints.\n\nAssessment\nThe patient's presentation is consistent with a right hand index finger contusion, likely involving the distal phalanx and joint.\n\nPlan\nPrescribe an aluminum foam splint and recommend 600 mg ibuprofen every six hours for one week. Advise the patient to call if symptoms do not improve within one week. Finalize report.",
  "reference_summary": "CC:\n\nRight finger pain.\n\nHPI:\n\nMs. Brooks is a 48-year-old female who presents today for an evaluation of right finger pain. She states she was skiing on Sunday and hyperextended her finger when it became caught in a strap on a jump. She has tried applying ice and taking Ibuprofen, but it is still very painful. She has pain with movement.\n\nCURRENT MEDICATIONS:\n\nMiraLax\n\nPAST MEDICAL HISTORY:\n\nConstipation.\n\nPAST SURGICAL HISTORY:\n\nAppendectomy.\n\nEXAM\n\nExamination of the right index finger shows tenderness over the distal phalanx. No tenderness over the proximal phalanx or the MP joint. Pain with flexion.\n\nRESULTS\n\nX-rays of the right hand show no obvious signs of fracture or bony abnormalities.\n\nIMPRESSION\n\nRight hand index finger contusion at the tip of the finger.\n\nPLAN\n\nAt this point, I discussed the diagnosis and treatment options with the patient. I have recommended a splint. She will take Motrin 600 mg every 6 hours for a week. If she does not improve, she will follow up with me. All questions were answered.",
